  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- DAY 1 — Apr 17 (Fri) · Arrival → Kyoto                -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <Folder>
    <name>Day 1 — Apr 17 (Fri) · Arrival → Kyoto</name>
    <description>Two arrival groups take JR Haruka straight from KIX to Kyoto. Full group reunites ~21:30 in Gion for a light first-night dinner and Pontocho drinks.</description>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Kansai International Airport (KIX)</name>
      <styleUrl>#day1-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>Arrivals</b><br>
        Cathay Pacific: Terminal 2 at 15:10<br>
        Cebu Pacific: Terminal 1 at 18:20<br><br>
        <b>To-do at KIX:</b><br>
        • Buy IC card (ICOCA) at JR Ticket Office<br>
        • ICOCA &amp; Haruka combo ~¥1,800 one-way — cheaper than standalone Haruka<br>
        • 75-min Haruka direct to Kyoto Station<br><br>
        <i>Cost: ¥1,800–3,640 per person</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.2441,34.4320,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Kyoto Station (Haruka arrival)</name>
      <styleUrl>#day1-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>~17:30 (CX group) / ~20:30 (5J group)</b><br>
        Hakurumachi central station — transfer point for Gion hotel.<br><br>
        <b>Onward to hotel:</b><br>
        • Taxi ~15 min / ¥1,500 split four ways<br>
        • Keihan Line to Gion-Shijo + 5-min walk (¥230)<br><br>
        <i>Haruka runs every ~30 min — plan for the 16:16 (CX) or 19:16 (5J) departure from KIX</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7588,34.9858,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Gion / Higashiyama — Hotel Check-In</name>
      <styleUrl>#day1-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>17:30–18:00 (CX group) / 21:00–21:30 (5J group)</b><br>
        Base for the first three nights of the trip.<br><br>
        Request early check-in for the CX group. If rooms aren't ready, leave bags with the front desk (standard in Japan).<br><br>
        <i>Full group reunites ~21:30 in Gion — head out together</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7756,35.0037,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Gion Evening Stroll (CX early arrivers)</name>
      <styleUrl>#day1-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>18:00–20:30 (CX group only)</b><br>
        Scout Hanamikoji Street, wander toward Pontocho, get a first taste of Kyoto evening.<br><br>
        • Possible geisha sightings 18:00–19:00 on Hanamikoji<br>
        • Matcha soft-serve or coffee stops along the way<br>
        • Kamo River walk if the weather is nice<br><br>
        <i>Don't over-do it — big day tomorrow</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7780,35.0036,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>First Group Dinner — Gion / Pontocho izakaya</name>
      <styleUrl>#day1-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>21:30–22:45 (Full group)</b><br>
        Casual first-night izakaya — sake, yakitori, small plates under paper lanterns.<br><br>
        <b>Options:</b><br>
        • Gion Tanto (¥2,500–4,000) — yakitori with sake pairings, counter seats, reserved<br>
        • <b>Gombei</b> (¥2,000–3,000, Bib Gourmand) — Gion Kitagawa soba specialist, walk-in friendly<br>
        • Gogyo Kyoto (¥2,000–3,000) — burnt-miso ramen, lively late hours<br>
        • Any Pontocho chōchin-lit izakaya — walk in wherever has space<br><br>
        <i>Cost: ¥2,000–3,500 per person</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7695,35.0074,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>BAR Atlantis — Riverside Drinks</name>
      <styleUrl>#day1-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>22:45–00:00 (Full group)</b><br>
        The only bar on Pontocho with an outdoor counter along the Kamo River — closest thing Kyoto has to a rooftop bar.<br><br>
        • House cocktails with river breeze and reflected lights<br>
        • No full kawadoko platforms until May 1, but outdoor counter is year-round<br>
        • Easy low-key intro to Kyoto nightlife<br><br>
        <i>Cost: ¥2,000–3,500 per person</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7697,35.0065,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Day 1 Route</name>
      <styleUrl>#day1-line</styleUrl>
      <LineString>
        <tessellate>1</tessellate>
        <coordinates>
          135.2441,34.4320,0
          135.7588,34.9858,0
          135.7756,35.0037,0
          135.7780,35.0036,0
          135.7695,35.0074,0
          135.7697,35.0065,0
        </coordinates>
      </LineString>
    </Placemark>
  </Folder>

  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- DAY 2 — Apr 18 (Sat) · Kyoto Day 1                    -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <Folder>
    <name>Day 2 — Apr 18 (Sat) · Kyoto Day 1</name>
    <description>Fushimi Inari + Fushimi sake in the morning, Ginkaku-ji + Philosopher's Path + Nanzen-ji + Southern Higashiyama in the afternoon, Pontocho Saturday night (nice izakaya + riverside bar). Budget: ¥14,000–24,000.</description>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Fushimi Inari Shrine</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>08:30–10:30</b><br>
        Over 10,000 vermillion torii gates winding up a forested mountain — one of Japan's most iconic sights.<br><br>
        • Entry: Free<br>
        • ⚡ Arrive by 08:30 — Saturday crowds swell fast<br>
        • Turn back at Yotsutsuji Intersection (~30 min up) for great views without the full summit loop<br><br>
        <b>Getting here:</b> Keihan Line from Gion-Shijo (¥210, 10 min)<br>
        <i>Cost: Free</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7727,34.9671,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Gekkeikan Okura Museum — Fushimi Sake District</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>10:45–12:00</b><br>
        Fushimi is Kyoto's sake-brewing district — ~40 breweries along a willow-lined canal, walkable from Fushimi Inari.<br><br>
        • Entry: ¥600 (includes tasting of 3 sakes + plum wine)<br>
        • 1909 brewery converted to museum with 400+ sake-making tools<br>
        • Willow-lined canal with white-walled kura (storehouses)<br><br>
        <b>Lunch 12:00–13:15:</b> Torisei (sake brewery restaurant) — yakitori + sake ¥1,500–2,500<br>
        <i>Cost: ¥600 + lunch</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7556,34.9380,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Ginkaku-ji (Silver Pavilion)</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>14:15–14:45</b><br>
        UNESCO World Heritage Zen temple with a celebrated sand garden and moss garden.<br><br>
        • Entry: ¥500<br>
        • Two-story wooden pavilion (never actually silver)<br>
        • Start of the Philosopher's Path<br><br>
        <b>Getting here:</b> Keihan → Demachiyanagi, then Bus #5 or #17 to Ginkaku-ji-michi (~45 min total, ¥440)<br>
        <i>Cost: ¥500</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7984,35.0270,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Omen Ginkaku-ji Honten — Udon (Bib Gourmand)</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>14:50–15:30 (optional)</b><br>
        ⭐ Bib Gourmand (2023). Classic Kyoto udon house on the Ginkaku-ji approach — thick hand-cut noodles, big tray of seasonal vegetables and sesame, dip yourself.<br><br>
        • ¥1,200–1,800 per person<br>
        • Walk-in friendly (Juugo nearby is typically booked weeks out — this is the reliable Bib option)<br>
        • Beautiful townhouse interior<br><br>
        <i>Skip if still full from Fushimi lunch — otherwise a proper Kyoto meal before the walk</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7970,35.0260,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Philosopher's Path (Tetsugaku no Michi)</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>15:00–16:00</b><br>
        ⭐ 2km canal-side walk lined with ~500 cherry trees — named after philosopher Nishida Kitaro who used it for daily meditation.<br><br>
        • Entry: Free<br>
        • ~40 min at a relaxed pace, Ginkaku-ji → Nanzen-ji<br>
        • Late cherry varieties may still be clinging on April 18<br>
        • Stop at Honen-in Temple (free) halfway — hidden moss-covered gate and Zen garden<br><br>
        <i>The reason we moved to three Kyoto days</i><br>
        <i>Cost: Free</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7949,35.0211,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Nanzen-ji Temple &amp; Aqueduct</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>16:00–16:45</b><br>
        Head temple of the Rinzai Zen sect, with a massive Sanmon gate and a Meiji-era brick aqueduct on the grounds.<br><br>
        • Grounds: Free<br>
        • Sanmon Gate (climb): ¥600<br>
        • Main hall gardens: ¥500<br>
        • Aqueduct is an incredible photo op — red brick framing the temple<br><br>
        <b>Getting here:</b> End of the Philosopher's Path (walkable from Ginkaku-ji)<br>
        <i>Cost: Free grounds / ¥500–600 extras</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7935,35.0112,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Kiyomizu-dera Temple</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>17:00–18:00</b><br>
        UNESCO World Heritage temple perched on a hillside with a famous wooden stage jutting over the valley.<br><br>
        • Entry: ¥500<br>
        • Closes 18:00 — don't arrive later than 17:00<br>
        • Wooden stage built without a single nail<br>
        • Late-afternoon light on the vermillion pagoda is the best of the day<br><br>
        <b>Getting here:</b> Bus #5 or #100 from Nanzen-ji (¥230, 15 min) or taxi (~¥1,200 split four ways)<br>
        <i>Cost: ¥500</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7850,34.9948,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Sannen-zaka + Hokan-ji (Yasaka) Pagoda</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>18:00–18:15</b><br>
        Preserved Edo-era slope past matcha shops and pickle stalls to the iconic five-story pagoda — the postcard Kyoto shot, best in late-afternoon light.<br><br>
        • Sannen-zaka: stone-paved matcha-ice-cream streets<br>
        • Hokan-ji Pagoda: vermillion five-story icon<br><br>
        <i>Cost: Free — ~15 min walk</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7784,35.0000,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Bar Kohaku — Park Hyatt Kyoto (Yasaka Pagoda view)</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>18:15–19:15 (Pre-dinner drinks)</b><br>
        ⭐ Intimate cocktail room with floor-to-ceiling windows facing <b>Yasaka Pagoda</b> — catch it at golden hour / blue hour.<br><br>
        • Head bartender Akiko Nakamura builds narrative cocktails around Kyoto history and ingredients<br>
        • Signature "Shuhari": sake + matcha + grapefruit<br>
        • Full <b>Ki No Bi Kyoto gin</b> lineup<br>
        • Polished hotel-bar vibe — use this for the civilized pre-dinner drink, not the late-night speakeasy<br><br>
        <i>📌 Reserve ahead — small room, Saturday golden-hour window fills</i><br>
        <i>Cost: ¥2,500–4,500 per person</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7815,35.0010,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Ninen-zaka → Maruyama → Yasaka → Gion → Pontocho</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>19:15–19:45</b><br>
        20–25 min descent from the pagoda through Maruyama Park (weeping cherry, possible late blooms) and Yasaka Shrine, across Hanamikoji (geisha spotting possible 18:00–19:00), over Shijo-Ohashi to Pontocho.<br><br>
        <i>Cost: Free</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7784,35.0037,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Pontocho — Saturday Dinner &amp; Drinks</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>19:45–00:00 (The Kyoto Saturday night)</b><br>
        Kyoto's narrow dining alley along the Kamo River — the most atmospheric street in Japan.<br><br>
        <b>Dinner (19:45):</b><br>
        • Hachidaime Gihey Kyoto — rice-focused kaiseki. ¥4,000–6,000. Reserve.<br>
        • <b>Isoyama</b> (Bib Gourmand) — Pontocho counter izakaya, charcoal-grilled fish + sake. ¥3,000–4,500<br>
        • Pontocho Robin — obanzai + sake flights. ¥3,500–5,500<br>
        • Gion Kappa — kushiage + sake, walk-in friendly. ¥3,000–4,500<br><br>
        <b>Drinks (21:15):</b><br>
        • <b>BAR Atlantis</b> — outdoor riverside counter, rooftop-bar feel. ¥2,500–4,000<br>
        • L'Escamoteur — theatrical cocktails by an illusionist. ¥2,500–4,000<br>
        • <b>The Book Store / Bee's Knees</b> (#76 Asia's 50 Best Bars 2025) — yellow door speakeasy, Prohibition aesthetic. ¥2,500–4,000<br><br>
        <i>Kyoto Saturday ≠ Osaka club Saturday — lean into the slower rhythm</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7697,35.0065,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Day 2 Route</name>
      <styleUrl>#day2-line</styleUrl>
      <LineString>
        <tessellate>1</tessellate>
        <coordinates>
          135.7756,35.0037,0
          135.7727,34.9671,0
          135.7556,34.9380,0
