          135.7697,35.0065,0
        </coordinates>
      </LineString>
    </Placemark>
  </Folder>

  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <!-- DAY 3 — Apr 19 (Sun) · Kyoto Day 2 (Arashiyama + Uji) -->
  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <Folder>
    <name>Day 3 — Apr 19 (Sun) · Arashiyama + Kinkakuji + Uji</name>
    <description>Bamboo grove at dawn, Golden Pavilion, matcha-making in Uji, farewell Kyoto dinner. Last Kyoto night before Osaka transfer. Budget: ¥13,000–22,000.</description>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Arashiyama Bamboo Grove</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>08:45–09:15</b><br>
        One of Japan's most photographed natural wonders — towering bamboo stalks filtering morning light.<br><br>
        • Entry: Free<br>
        • ⚡ 08:45 is the last clean window before Sunday tour groups<br>
        • Path is 500m long<br>
        • Rickshaw rides available ¥4,000–13,000<br><br>
        <b>Getting here:</b> Kyoto Station → Saga-Arashiyama (JR Sagano Line, 15 min, ¥240)<br>
        <i>Cost: Free</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.6728,35.0163,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Tenryu-ji Temple &amp; Gardens</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>09:15–10:30</b><br>
        UNESCO World Heritage Zen temple with a stunning garden designed in 1339.<br><br>
        • Garden entry: ¥500 | Temple buildings: ¥900<br>
        • Sogen Pond garden with Arashiyama mountain as "borrowed scenery"<br>
        • Shigetsu restaurant (shojin ryori) inside — ¥3,000–5,500, reserve<br><br>
        <i>⏭️ Skippable: Monkey Park Iwatayama (¥600) or Hozugawa river boat (¥4,100)</i><br>
        <i>Cost: ¥500–900</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.6750,35.0150,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Togetsukyo Bridge &amp; Katsura River</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>10:30–11:00</b><br>
        Classic Arashiyama postcard — a wooden bridge across the Katsura River with mountains behind.<br><br>
        • Free scenic walk along the riverfront<br>
        • Good spot for group photos<br><br>
        <i>Lunch 11:00 — Shigetsu (shojin ryori) or casual café/noodle shop</i><br>
        <i>Cost: Free</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.6774,35.0127,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Kinkakuji — Golden Pavilion</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>13:00–14:00</b><br>
        Kyoto's most iconic sight — a Zen temple covered in gold leaf, perfectly reflected in the pond.<br><br>
        • Entry: ¥500<br>
        • One-way path around the pond — 1 hour is plenty<br>
        • Originally built 1397, rebuilt 1955 after arson<br><br>
        <b>Getting here:</b> Bus #93 from Arashiyama (40 min, ¥460)<br>
        <i>Cost: ¥500</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7292,35.0394,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Fukujuen Uji Kobo — Matcha Experience</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>15:00–16:30</b><br>
        ⭐ Grind your own matcha with a traditional stone mill, then whisk and drink what you made.<br><br>
        • Cost: ¥1,650<br>
        • Fukujuen is one of Japan's most respected tea companies (since 1790)<br>
        • Browse premium loose-leaf matcha to buy as souvenirs<br><br>
        <b>Getting here:</b> Bus back to Kyoto Station → JR Nara Line to Uji (~45 min total, ¥700)<br>
        <i>📌 BOOK AHEAD online or by phone</i><br>
        <i>Cost: ¥1,650</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.8032,34.8856,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Byodo-in Temple — Uji</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>16:30–17:30</b><br>
        UNESCO World Heritage temple — the image on Japan's 10-yen coin.<br><br>
        • Entry: ¥600 garden + ¥300 Phoenix Hall<br>
        • Phoenix Hall (Ho-odo): built 1053, virtually unchanged since<br>
        • Pond reflection of the temple is the money shot<br><br>
        <b>Then 17:15–18:00:</b> Browse Uji tea shops; matcha soft-serve, matcha parfait, hojicha sweets (¥800–1,500)<br>
        <i>Cost: ¥600</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.8063,34.8884,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Farewell Kyoto Dinner — Pontocho / Gion</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-pin</styleUrl>
      <description><![CDATA[
        <b>19:00–21:00</b><br>
        Last Kyoto meal before Osaka transfer tomorrow morning.<br><br>
        <b>Options:</b><br>
        • Gion Karyo — mini-kaiseki in a Gion machiya. ¥5,000–8,000. Reserve.<br>
        • Omen Gion — thick hand-cut udon in a beautiful townhouse. ¥2,000–3,500<br>
        • Nishiki Warai — casual okonomiyaki / obanzai near Nishiki Market. ¥2,500–4,000<br><br>
        <b>Last drinks (21:00):</b> The Book Store, Bar Bunkyu, or second visit to BAR Atlantis<br>
        <i>Cost: ¥4,000–8,000 + drinks</i>
      ]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>135.7697,35.0065,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>

    <Placemark>
      <name>Day 3 Route</name>
      <styleUrl>#day3-line</styleUrl>
      <LineString>
        <tessellate>1</tessellate>
        <coordinates>
          135.7756,35.0037,0
          135.6728,35.0163,0
